  scenario="It is 8pm on a Friday. A homeowner in Botley has been browsing extension company Facebook pages all evening with her husband. They have a 1930s semi-detached house with a rear reception room, a separate kitchen, and a narrow side passage. An architect friend has suggested they could open the side return, knock through the rear reception and kitchen, and extend out three metres — creating one large L-shaped kitchen-dining-family space. She finds your page, scrolls through five completed extension projects — all showing the same kind of transformation — and messages: 'Hi — we have a 1930s semi and want to open the side return and extend at the rear. Our architect friend has done rough sketches. The side passage is about 1 metre wide. Do you handle party walls as part of the build? And can you advise on whether this needs planning or would come under PD?' Without AI Facebook Messenger, you see the message Saturday lunchtime after a morning on site. She has also messaged two other companies; one replied at 8:15pm Friday with a helpful explanation of PD limits for semi-detached properties. With AI Messenger, the reply arrives at 8:01pm: 'Thank you — side return and rear extensions on semi-detached houses are one of our most popular project types. We coordinate party wall agreements as standard. Could you share your postcode and your friend's sketches? One of our team will call you to discuss PD eligibility and arrange a visit.' She sends the sketches and her postcode. Saturday morning you open the lead: 1930s semi, side return plus rear extension, L-shaped kitchen-diner, 1m side passage, party wall needed, PD query, architect sketches attached, Botley. You call at 9am, discuss PD for semi-detached houses, and book a Tuesday evening consultation."
